    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3991464759" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3991464759" />
    <a title="Sam Brown" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38171087-sam-brown"><img alt="Sam Brown" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626382289p2/38171087.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3991464759?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam Brown" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam Brown" href="/user/show/38171087-sam-brown">Sam Brown</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/26157078-animal-liberation">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38171087-sam-brown?shelf=my-2021-in-books">my-2021-in-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38171087-sam-brown?shelf=best-shit-ever">best-shit-ever</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3991464759" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5707819835849673498">It is often said that the 20th century is the most brutal period in human history. Certainly, there is a case to be made that the genocides of Nazi Germany, Stalinist Russia, Imperial Japan or modern Rwanda meets this criterion, both when considered in combination with one another or considered separately. We like to imagine these infamous, modern conflicts as largely disconnected incidents, feeding into one another whilst remaining broadly independent situations. As such, we refer to them with </span>
  <span id="freeText5707819835849673498" style="display:none">It is often said that the 20th century is the most brutal period in human history. Certainly, there is a case to be made that the genocides of Nazi Germany, Stalinist Russia, Imperial Japan or modern Rwanda meets this criterion, both when considered in combination with one another or considered separately. We like to imagine these infamous, modern conflicts as largely disconnected incidents, feeding into one another whilst remaining broadly independent situations. As such, we refer to them with banal but specific terms like World War I, World War II, the Sino-Japanese War, Communist Russia, and more. These terms and events obviously encompass much in and of themselves but they are designed to create a wall of separation; we recognise, of course, that World War I led to World War II, but we visualise them in our minds as separate events. This is a byproduct of the human obsession for categorisation, an obsession that works really well in bringing complicated subjects into our realm of understanding, especially for the layperson. As a consequence, however, we ignore the fact that these are not separate events; instead, they are the culmination and continuation of a multitude of factors. <br /><br />For this reason, I am a fan of Matthew White's description of the early-to-mid 20th century as "The Hemoclysm" (in other words, 'The Bloodbath'). Rather than separating "World War I" from "The Russian Civil War" which is separate from "Imperial Japan", etc., White conceives of all these separate incidents as one long historical event, starting with the decline of the Ottoman Empire and ending with the death of Mao. This concept was introduced to me by Canadian political columnist J. J. McCullough and I like it because it encompasses the entire remit of the 20th century, understanding, of course, that one historical event is inextricably tied to all the others. We are the product of Genghis Khan as much as we are the product of Donald Trump, as much as we are the product of the Holocaust and the Agricultural Revolution and the Israel/Palestine conflict and literally everything that's ever happened during the course of history.<br /><br />With White's concept of The Hemoclysm in mind, I think it is accurate to describe the long and sad history of human relations with non-human animals as "The Anthroclysm" - the factory farms of today are a continuation and a predictor of our sordid abuse of these individuals, encompassing Christian 'dominionship' over non-human animals to Decarte's 'Meditations' to Darwin's theory of evolution to the dead cow that I ate at Wetherspoons five years ago for just £6.99 (at least it included a free drink!). So much of modern vegan philosophy is built around opposition to factory farms and industry-induced climate change - rightly so! - but it doesn't engage with the fundamental issue of carnivorousness; if a pig lived a long, beautiful and happy life, free from stress, pain or danger, it would still be immoral to kill it before its time (even shortly before its time) just for the sake of taste sensation. This is such an obvious truism that it boggles the mind how I, or anyone else, ever thought or (as is, unfortunately, the case for the majority of humans currently alive today) thinks it is acceptable to murder a conscious being just because it's yummy. It is so depressing to think of the billions upon billions upon billions of innocent beings who died to procure a tasty meal, especially in today's world where vegan and veggie alternatives can be just as tasty, inexpensive and nutritional as non-vegan/veggie food. As such, there is an argument to be made - an argument reflected in Singer's seminal treatise- that The Anthroclysm is the singular worst thing ever committed by humans, even stacked up against The Hemoclysm. Perhaps not on an individual level - a human being is definitely worth more than a pig - but certainly on a collective level. The belief that we have a right to eat meat is the seed from which modern animal atrocities sprouts. To argue that our subjugation of the non-human animal matches or exceeds the immortality of The Hemoclysm is... controversial. It also happens to be true. And I can prove it with maths.<br /><br />"If you're on an island with a pig and another human, and you're starving to death-"<br /><br />Of course I would eat the pig. But whether a non-human animal has the same moral worth as a human is irrelevant to whether we should eat them. Singer pretty definitely proved this. Humans could have tenfold the moral worth of a non-human animal and it would be irrelevant. What matters, ultimately, is whether it is moral to kill something in order to have a tasty meal when tasty meals that don't result in the death of innocent beings are readily available (and usually better for you). However, I am extremely interested in this question: when does the moral value of a non-human animal reach that of a human? While irrelevant, it does elucidate just HOW horrifying The Anthroclysm is, historically and currently. Thinking about this over several months and years is also what finally motivated me to go vegan. This review has become self-indulgent anyway so, if you're not already sold on the prospect of veganism, I hope this might sway your opinion. <br /><br />Here we go:<br /><br />Given the option to kill one random human being or every non-human animal in existence, which should you kill? Even the most ardent meat-eater would conclude it is better, at least in the context of this abstract thought experiment, to kill the human. Not just because the worth of a single human being is microscopic in comparison to every non-human in existence but because a world without any non-human animals would be catastrophic for humans as well. Aside from disturbing the natural order of the entire world, it would set humans at a massive disadvantage; every pet, guide dog and service animal would be gone. It would also be lonely. It's sad to imagine that we're the only planet that allows for the proliferation of life, let alone the only cognizant species in existence. Yes, the human in question probably (not definitely) has a family and friends and a social circle - even if this random human didn't have these things, their life is still sacred - but it's clearly outweighed when stacked against the life of every non-human on Earth, if not for non-humans then certainly for the humans left in the aftermath of this hypothetical dystopia. This establishes that, at a certain point, the preference of non-humans outweighs that of humans. <br /><br />This is the point at which I decided that veganism was better than the alternative - unfortunately, it didn't fully motivate me to go vegan because I'm lazy and, apparently, I hate acting in accordance with my own principles. I tried a few times but I always failed because meat tastes amazing. There's no getting around that fact. Burgers taste amazing. Pizza tastes amazing. Bacon tastes amazing.<br /><br />But let's take the thought experiment further. What if you had to choose between the life of a human being or the life of every other non-human animal... bar one? Say, for instance, a pig. One human or every non-human animal except for a single pig. You'd probably still choose to kill the human. Again, if not for non-humans then for humans, who would lose every dog, cat and non-vegan meatball in existence. Okay, how about two non-human animals? A pig and, say, a chicken? Again, it would be more morally acceptable for one human being to die than every non-human animal bar two. If you keep doing this - adding another non-human animal every time - you would eventually come to the Magical Number, the Magical Number at which point you can say, "No, save the human instead". This is the point at which the preferences of a human outweigh a non-human. I'm not sure what that Magical Number is because I've never completed the thought experiment enough times to whittle it down. To do so would take longer than the heat death of the universe. But I would say, for the sake of argument, you could make a good case for 1000. The moral consideration of 1000 non-humans equals 1 human. So, if you had to pick between saving the life of one human or one thousand non-humans, which would you pick? For me, I suppose it would be a coin toss. If you asked me to save one human or 999 non-humans, I'd save the former. If it was one human versus 1001 non-animals, I'd save the latter. <br /><br />This is a pretty crude and largely trivial calculation, for two main reasons. Firstly, I've picked 1000 because it's a round number at the end of a number sequence created by humans in order to understand the world. It's not a particularly special number. I've not chosen it as a result of a careful, methodical calculation and, when dealing with the lives of sentient beings, you really should count carefully. It's just an easy number to understand because to come to a more accurate number would require infinite time. Secondly, I've not specified which non-human animal. If you asked that question in regards to fish, most people would probably conceive a number much higher. If you asked that question in regards to dogs, the number might be lower - say, around the 100 mark, maybe even nearer to 10 depending on how much you love dogs (I love dogs!). The first problem is unavoidable and the second problem is deliberate. We view pigs as less morally valuable than dogs. The reason for this is that... we like dogs. But just because we like a species more doesn't mean it's worth more. You could argue dogs give humans more pleasure and, therefore, are worth more, but if you had to chose between a dog with no family, human or otherwise, or a pig with no family, which would you chose to kill? Intuitively, I'd say a dog, even if we assume that this specific dog can't bring joy to a human. And the reason for that is because I live in a society which values the life of a dog more than the life of a pig even though both are of comparable intelligence. <br /><br />So, we've got our Magical Number - at least, a placeholder Magical Number. It stands to reason, therefore, that if we need to chose between the life of 100 humans or 10,000 animals, it would be a coin toss. If it was 99 humans, we should save the 10,000 animals; if it was 9999 animals, we should save the humans. Working out how immoral The Anthroclysm is compared to human-on-human atrocities should be easy, then. We just need to compare how many people died throughout these conflicts versus how many animals we kill. <br /><br />The Hemoclysm - which, again, includes everything from World War I to World War II to the genocidal regimes of Hitler and Stalin - killed 150 million people. That is a number so impossibly big that a human mind can't comprehend it. The population of the UK is 65 million. The Hemoclysm artificially (I can't stress the word "artificially" in this sentence enough - they were not natural deaths from old age, these deaths did not have to happen and they occurred, largely, for no good reason) killed almost 2.5 times the population of the UK. The population of America is 320 million so imagine a historical event in which almost half of Americans die. The largest war-related death toll in American history, by the way, was the Civil War, which resulted in the death of 2% of the population. Remember as well, that is 150 million people who had friends and family, all taken away. So, assuming 1 human equals 1000 animals, the Anthroclysm would need to kill 150 billion non-humans - that's billion with a capital B. You thought 150 million was too large a number to understand? 150 billion is so large a number that it barely qualifies as a number. It's closer to a theoretical concept, like wormholes or faster-than-light travel.<br /><br />So, how many animals do we kill? In a single year - just a YEAR - we kill 150 billion non-humans. That is so ridiculous and crazy that it's absurd. Words do no justice to those numbers. What that means, of course, is that every TWO years, we kill 300 billion non-humans - assuming 1 human = 1000 non-humans, that's DOUBLE the moral atrocity of The Hemoclysm - World War I, World War II, even the Holocaust. There is quite literally no argument to be made here. How did this happen? How can anyone justify this? Our twisted, Lovecraftian relationship to non-human animals is almost mathematically the worst atrocity in the history of mankind. <br /><br />150 BILLION, for f*ck sake. <br /><br />Animal liberation NOW.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5707819835849673498" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


