<div id="review_4222749106" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4222749106" />
    <a title="Obada Kattih" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92511297-obada-kattih"><img alt="Obada Kattih" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595302473p2/92511297.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4222749106?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Obada Kattih" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Obada Kattih" href="/user/show/92511297-obada-kattih">Obada Kattih</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4222749106" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10226093411027723463">&quot;If we have learned anything from liberation movements we should have learned how difficult it is to be aware of latent prejudices in our attitudes to particular groups until these prejudices are forcefully pointed out to us.&quot; <br/> <br/>Animal Liberation is an immensely powerful book that is as relevant today as it was during its publication in 1975, if not more so. Peter Singer makes the most compelling and irrefutable argument for the better treatment of animals. This book does not appeal to sympathy o</span>
  <span id="freeText10226093411027723463" style="display:none">"If we have learned anything from liberation movements we should have learned how difficult it is to be aware of latent prejudices in our attitudes to particular groups until these prejudices are forcefully pointed out to us." <br /> <br />Animal Liberation is an immensely powerful book that is as relevant today as it was during its publication in 1975, if not more so. Peter Singer makes the most compelling and irrefutable argument for the better treatment of animals. This book does not appeal to sympathy or emotion (although the very nature of what is often described will inadvertently arouse sympathy for most readers), but to reason and logic. This is a book of philosophy, and Singer argues that we have absolutely no logical grounds for treating animals the way we currently do. In fact, the same arguments that allowed us to fight against racism, sexism, and other forms of discrimination among humans, actually extend to animals as well. He uses the terms speciesism (discrimination against beings not of the same species), and demonstrates that this ideological discrimination is so ingrained in our society that we are often even unaware of it, but the parallels between it and past forms of prejudice and discrimination are clearly there - hence the name Animal <i>Liberation</i>.<br /><br />Unfortunately it appears that many issues discussed in this book are still largely plaguing our society today. We are woefully ignorant of the practices that are required to bring us meat to the dining table. We buy our meat in neat plastic packages, completely separated from the gruesome reality that takes place. We are also completely unaware of the horrible experiments performed on animals that take place in laboratories. As someone in the medical field, I thought I would find this section rather uncompelling, but I could not have been more wrong. <br /><br />Besides arguing against speciesism and exploring the current practices of our society and their immorality, Singer also spends time exploring the history of our attitude towards animals, particularly the influence of Greek, Christian, and Renaissance thought on that attitude. He also spends a chapter debunking many of the common arguments that are often heard by adversaries of animal welfare advocates and vegetarians (animals eat other animals in nature, what if plants can suffer, etc.). <br /><br />After reading this book, I cannot help but change my dietary habits. Once again, this is a philosophical work, not a vegan cult book. The book stresses that any change is positive, and the key factor to take into consideration is the suffering that took place. Therefore, there is nothing wrong with eating ethically obtained eggs, and eating scallops and shrimps would be significantly better than eating steak, and eating grass fed steak is also significantly better than eating factory farmed steak. I am quite fond of meat and consume it regularly, but I cannot in good conscious continue this practice without at least trying to change my diet, and I challenge anyone to read this book and not do the same. <br /><br />People often ask about what future generations would judge our society today for in the same way that we judge previous societies for atrocities such as slavery. This book leaves no doubt in my mind that the object that we will be judged for is our treatment of animals. If you have any interest in removing yourself from a prevalent form of discrimination, in becoming more knowledgeable about a topic you are likely ignorant of, or in becoming a more moral person, you should read this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10226093411027723463" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


