<div id="review_2964649934" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2964649934" />
    <a title="Talenelat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59737478-talenelat"><img alt="Talenelat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611310162p2/59737478.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2964649934?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Talenelat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Talenelat" href="/user/show/59737478-talenelat">Talenelat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59737478-talenelat?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59737478-talenelat?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59737478-talenelat?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2964649934" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9456033211440287885"><b>
  <i>“Philosophy ought to question the basic assumptions of the age. Thinking through, critically and carefully, what most of us take for granted is, I believe, the chief task of philosophy, and the task that makes philosophy a worthwhile activity.”</i>
</b><br/><br/>Animal Liberation is a defense of animal lives and a counter to an injustice Singer calls spieciesism, which he ranks beside slavery, racism, and sexism.<br/><br/>In the first chapter Peter Singer supplies the moral argument against the killing of animals. To me</span>
  <span id="freeText9456033211440287885" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>“Philosophy ought to question the basic assumptions of the age. Thinking through, critically and carefully, what most of us take for granted is, I believe, the chief task of philosophy, and the task that makes philosophy a worthwhile activity.”</i>
</b><br /><br />Animal Liberation is a defense of animal lives and a counter to an injustice Singer calls spieciesism, which he ranks beside slavery, racism, and sexism.<br /><br />In the first chapter Peter Singer supplies the moral argument against the killing of animals. To me, it was also a spotlight upon an inconsistency our society have fallen for.<br />The two following chapters expose both the use of animals for research and the current state of farm animals.<br />The fourth chapter proposes an alternative, a way to combat the injustice spoken about in length in the previous chapters.<br />In the fifth chapter Singer examines the history of speciesism and how we got to where we are today.<br />The last chapter is a response to some arguments that have been made against what the author preaches.<br /><br />I found this book to be quite impressive. I have started reading this book quite convinced of the arguments Singer will make, and came out even more convinced. You may call me out for having a confirmation bias there, and I only have my word to say that it is not the case.<br />This is most importantly not an emotional book. Singer will not appeal to your love for animals, he will instead make his point as if you have no emotion whatsoever towards them.<br />Animal Liberation is a logical book rooted in moral philosophy. It suffices to read a few pages, or preferably the first chapter to see what that means. I may call it one of the most logical things I have ever read.<br />I must also say that I see myself becoming a fan of Peter Singer, I will go on to read his books on ethics.<br />I have no noteworthy critique.<br /><br />I recommend this book to everyone. You can and maybe should only commit to reading the first chapter. It is not long and will only take you less than an hour to go through.<br />No matter where you stand in relation to the subject, you should, if not must, allow your ideas and pre-existing views to be challenged. <br /><br />I will not state what reading this book did to my views as I deem it not necessary to prove a point.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9456033211440287885" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


