    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4190436592" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4190436592" />
    <a title="Dunigan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40859577-dunigan"><img alt="Dunigan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611342033p2/40859577.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4190436592?book_show_action=true">Aug 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dunigan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dunigan" href="/user/show/40859577-dunigan">Dunigan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/40229444-animal-liberation">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4190436592" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15206672233243488955">I had a secret hope that reading this book would turn me into a vegetarian. As it turns out, I still plan on eating meat for the foreseeable future. I suppose it&apos;s a good thing that my mom will still be able to make her chicken casserole for me when I&apos;m home, and that there won&apos;t be more fodder for the dinner table conversations revolving around how the &quot;West Coast has changed me&quot;. Yet, I don&apos;t think my lack of conversion to a vegan/vegetarian diet is any indictment on the strength of Singer&apos;s a</span>
  <span id="freeText15206672233243488955" style="display:none">I had a secret hope that reading this book would turn me into a vegetarian. As it turns out, I still plan on eating meat for the foreseeable future. I suppose it's a good thing that my mom will still be able to make her chicken casserole for me when I'm home, and that there won't be more fodder for the dinner table conversations revolving around how the "West Coast has changed me". Yet, I don't think my lack of conversion to a vegan/vegetarian diet is any indictment on the strength of Singer's arguments in the book—it's more a testament to my comfort with hypocrisy.<br /><br />There are couple parts to this book. The very first part is where Singer lays out the his initial arguments against "speciesism" —discrimination based on the fact that a being belongs to a specific species. I found this part really compelling. I've heard speciesism thrown around a lot lately, but I hadn't really taken any time to fully sit with exactly what speciesism entails. Singer argues that because animals can feel pain, we have no justifiable reasons for giving them lesser consideration solely because they are, say, a chicken and not a human being. A classic argument in favor of treating animals worse than humans (or at least with less care) is that they are less "intelligent" than human beings. Yet, according to Singer, intelligence should rarely come into consideration when it comes to matters of experiencing pain. Pain is pain, and whether or not an animal can conceive of abstract intellectual ideas in their head should have no bearing on how much weight we give to their suffering—because it rarely effects how much suffering they experience. Of course, there are some situations where the intelligence of a human could make them suffer even more than an animal (humans in a factory farm could conceivably suffer more than animals because they would be aware of their eventual end). In these cases, it's fine to take intelligence into account, because it effects the amount of suffering created by certain actions, but for the majority of cases, intelligence will have no bearing on the amount of suffering induced. And it's in exactly these cases that it should make no difference to us what species the being belongs to. Any situation in which we condone unnecessary suffering solely because it's "an animal" is pure speciesism, and Singer puts speciesism on par with many other forms of discrimination —like sexism or racism. <br /><br />Singer uses some provocative examples to make his point. He suggests that a consequence of our harsh treatment and lack of care for "lesser" animals (e.g., chickens) based on their lower intelligence, is that we should have a similar disdain for severely disabled humans or very young children. After all, they are seriously intellectual disabled, and since we use low intelligence to justify our treatment of chickens, couldn't we too use that same justification for the maltreatment of these people? The fact that we don't treat disabled humans with the same disdain that we treat animals with is an example of speciesism to Singer. Of course, Singer is not advocating that we start treating disabled humans the same way we treat farm animals. Instead, he is using this example to show how fucked up our treatment of animals is, and how unjustified we are to be using "intelligence" as a reason for our maltreatment.<br /><br />The parts of the book where Singer is arguing against speciesism (the beginning and the end of the book) were by far my favorite. Unfortunately, it's not a large portion of the book. Singer spends a lot of time highlighting just how how horrible animal laboratory testing and factory farming is. Given that this book was written in the 70's I can see how this would have been eye opening to many readers at the time. However, in 2020, these sections were largely telling me things I already know. I am aware that factory farming is an absolutely grotesque display of animal maltreatment, and so 50 pages on the topic was probably unnecessary for me. I did, however, really enjoy his argument in favor of vegetarianism in the middle of the book. I think he gives a lot of compelling reasons for going vegetarian or vegan, and I totally buy that it is morally unjustifiable of me to eat meat —especially factory farmed meat.<br /><br />So, if I buy every argument laid out in this book, and I believe that it's morally unjustifiable to eat meat, then why am I not currently a vegetarian?? I don't know. I think it's just pure hypocrisy and laziness at this point. I don't have any other excuses. Someday, I think I will take the plunge, but I just can't take the first step. For now, I will continue to enjoy my mom's chicken casserole, knowing that I am unjustified in doing so.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15206672233243488955" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


