        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3445677660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12567949082515932896">(See my YouTube Review and Discussion here: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://youtu.be/rX392c3fp2s'>https://youtu.be/rX392c3fp2s</a> )<br/><br/>&quot;The question is not, Can they reason? nor Can they talk? but, Can they suffer?” // Jeremy Bentham, ‘The Principles of Morals and Legislation’ (1988).<br/><br/>This is one of the most important books that I&apos;ve ever read. Singer appeals to reason and not anecdotal arguments from emotion. The argument for *minimising* the suffering of non-human animals (within reason) is irrefutable as far as I&apos;m concerned.<br/><br/>The individual owes themselv</span>
  <span id="freeText12567949082515932896" style="display:none">(See my YouTube Review and Discussion here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/rX392c3fp2s">https://youtu.be/rX392c3fp2s</a> )<br /><br />"The question is not, Can they reason? nor Can they talk? but, Can they suffer?” // Jeremy Bentham, ‘The Principles of Morals and Legislation’ (1988).<br /><br />This is one of the most important books that I've ever read. Singer appeals to reason and not anecdotal arguments from emotion. The argument for *minimising* the suffering of non-human animals (within reason) is irrefutable as far as I'm concerned.<br /><br />The individual owes themselves the justice to recognise the true nature of what we unnecessarily subject non-human animals to in the pursuit to satisfy our tastebuds. Thus; I believe everyone should read this book because of how, if followed, the message positively impacts the world in numerous stripes.</span>
